          <ArticleSubPage id="1488" parentID="1485" level="5" writerID="5" creatorID="5" nodeType="1181" template="1113" sortOrder="3" createDate="2007-02-10T00:00:00" updateDate="2011-11-24T19:12:36" nodeName="Restoring and creating and Outlook backup" urlName="restoring-and-creating-and-outlook-backup" writerName="rubenski" creatorName="rubenski" path="-1,1277,1278,1281,1485,1488" isDoc="">
            <positionInArticle>
            </positionInArticle>
            <body><![CDATA[
<p>Email messages may contain important information that you don't
want to lose. Creating backups is essential if you depend on your
email messages for important information. In this chapter I will
show you how to backup and restore your Outlook email folders
manually.</p>

<h2>The PST file</h2>

<p>In the email environment we are using in this tutorial, all
Outlook data is stored on the local machine in a PST file. (This is
different if you use an Exchange Server mailbox). The PST file
contains email messages, Contacts and Calender entries. Creating a
backup of Outlook data is simply a matter of copying the PST file
somewhere else, somewhere safe preferably.</p>

<p>If you use Windows XP, the PST file is usually located in
C:\Documents and Settings\&lt;your_computer_account_name&gt;\Local
Settings\Application Data\Microsoft\Outlook\. If you don't see the
PST file it may be hidden. You can let Windows Explorer show hidden
files by (in Windows Explorer) selecting Tools &gt; Folder
Options... &gt; select 'View'-tab &gt; Select 'Show hidden files
and folders' and click OK.</p>

<p>If you are not sure where your PST file is located, right-click
'Personal Folders' in the folder tree in the left pane and choose
'Properties for Personal Folders'. In the properties windows click
the Advanced... button. The location of the PST field is displayed
in the filename field.</p>

<p>Once found, close Outlook and copy the PST file to another
location, preferably a CD or DVD, because they can be stored
safely.</p>

<h2>Restoring an Outlook backup</h2>

<p>Creating and restoring email backups is not as elegant as you
might expect from a popular email client like Outlook. Especially
restoring a backup is a bit complicated. Follow the steps below to
restore an Outlook email backup.</p>

<ol>
<li>Copy the PST backup file to your harddisk and remember the
location. You will need it later.</li>

<li>In Windows (Xp or 2000) go to Start &gt; Settings &gt; Control
Panel &gt;Mail and click the E-mail Accounts... button.
Alternatively, select Tools &gt; E-mail Accounts... in
Outlook.</li>

<li>Choose 'Add a new e-mail account' and click NEXT</li>

<li>Choose POP3 and click NEXT</li>

<li>Fill out the proper info in the POP3 setup window that appears
and click NEXT. (Read page 2 of this tutorial if you want don't
know what to fill out)</li>

<li>Click Finish</li>

<li>Repeat step 2, but now choose 'View or change existing e-mail
accounts'. <img src="/static/images/e-mailaccounts.gif" width="501&quot;" height="377" alt="E-mail"/></li>

<li>In the white pane select the email account you just created and
click the 'New Outlook Data File' button.</li>

<li>In the 'New Outlook Data File' window that now appears select
Office Outlook Personal Folder File (.pst) and click OK.
Alternatively, if you are restoring an Outlook 97, 98, 2000 or 2002
pst file, choose the lower option.</li>

<li>Now select the PST file you copied to your harddisk in step 1
of this tutorial and click OK.</li>

<li>Finally you can set the 'Deliver new e-mail to the following
location' option (see image above) to the correct location.</li>
</ol>

<p>The new email account you set up now uses the backup PST file.
Especially when working with multiple email accounts you are
advised to give sensible names and locations to your PST files so
you can always tell them apart!</p>
]]></body>
