        <BlogCommentsFolder id="1712" parentID="1682" level="4" writerID="6" creatorID="5" nodeType="1663" template="0" sortOrder="1" createDate="2011-12-16T16:52:51" updateDate="2011-12-16T16:52:55" nodeName="Comments" urlName="comments" writerName="visitor" creatorName="rubenski" path="-1,1277,1641,1682,1712" isDoc="">
          <BlogComment id="1713" parentID="1712" level="5" writerID="6" creatorID="6" nodeType="1661" template="0" sortOrder="1" createDate="2011-12-16T16:52:58" updateDate="2011-12-16T16:53:01" nodeName="Comment by Hafidz" urlName="comment-by-hafidz" writerName="visitor" creatorName="visitor" path="-1,1277,1641,1682,1712,1713" isDoc="">
            <name>Hafidz</name>
            <email>hafidz.mohamed@gmail.com</email>
            <message><![CDATA[This is my experience with the problem of &quot;touchpad pointer jumping around like crazy when touched&quot;. At first thought effected by a virus. Various efforts have been made ​​such as virus scan, defrag and re format, the results remain the same. I also get the solution on the internet including delete touchpad drivers (Synaptics) and install it again .. the result is the same.
 Eventually, I found the solution from Davron (http://forum.notebookreview.com/averatec/26711-cursor-jumping-around-4.html)
 Thank you DAV
 He said the problem may come from AC / DC power supply unit. I continue to draw out AC / DC jack from my laptop ... BAMMMM! The problem finally finished. My touchpad works normal again.
 Hope this information will resolve your problem.
 From the innovators Hafidz my
]]></message>
          </BlogComment>
        </BlogCommentsFolder>
